{
  "text": "These results open a potentially new and critical field of study, overlapping fields of education and health, possibly involving policymaking, and vital for both the well-being of students and their productivity in terms of academic development. While the former area warrants potential prevention to avoid long-term health burden for society, the latter may add new perspective to the debates on already pending need of optimization of educational systems [CITATION_1] . The potential far-reaching implications of this line research may become more evident, if we take into consideration that improving the quality and efficiency of education and training, as well as making lifelong learning fact, are among the main objectives of strategic frameworks of policymaking institutions (e.g., European Commission, 2015). However, more data concerning study addiction are needed from different countries, cultures, and educational systems from all over the world as well as clinical validation as to whether it genuinely exists.",
